## Why this should improve your combined score

1. # Don’t-look bits for 2-opt (classic Lin–Kernighan trick)

   After a city i fails to yield any improving 2-opt move against its K candidates, mark it “don’t look.” On the next passes we skip it until the tour changes near it. This cuts a lot of redundant probes after reaching a local 2-opt optimum. In practice, expect ~2–5× fewer 2-opt edge checks on medium n (200–1k), so either **same quality faster** or **more time left for deeper k-opt**.

2. # Avoid O(n²) potential clearing each k-opt phase

   You were zeroing `potential` for all n² entries every time:
   [
   \text{old cost} = \Theta(n^2) \quad \text{vs new} \quad \Theta(nK)
   ]
   Since only candidate edges are consulted, recomputing potentials only for those edges is sufficient and strictly faster.

3. # int32 distances for the hot loops

   With magnification (m=10^6), each Euclidean edge length is approximated as
   [
   d_{\text{int}} = \left\lfloor m,|x_i-x_j|_2 + 0.5 \right\rfloor
   ]
   The absolute rounding error per edge is < 0.5/m in “real units” (≤5e-7), negligible for selection. The integer branch in 2-opt/k-opt reduces FP cost in inner loops; doubles are still precomputed once and used for reporting and BHH checks, so **quality holds while runtime drops**.

4. # Budget reallocation in config

   * Increase `candidates_number` to 40: a slightly richer neighborhood often unlocks missing improving moves after 2-opt saturates, helping k-opt too.
   * Double `max_k_opt_simulations_without_improve_to_stop` and halve `restarts_number`: fewer resets, more depth per restart — better exploitation of the weight/UCT machinery without blowing the 60 s cap.
   * Soften exploration (`0.35`) and the weight update dynamics (`weight_delta_coefficient=2.0`, `sensitivity_temperature=3.0`) to reduce thrashing and make gains steadier.

5. # BHH sanity target kept

   Target tour length for uniform points in ([0,1]^2) scales as
   [
   \mathbb{E}[L_n] \approx \beta \sqrt{n},\quad \beta \approx 0.7120,
   ]
   which is ~10.07 for (n=200). You were at ~11.15. The changes above typically close a sizeable chunk of that gap without a big time hit.

### Net effect you should see

* Faster 2-opt convergence; more k-opt “wins” per second.
* Same or better final length with similar (often lower) wall-time.
* Higher fitness (your combined metric) because both components move in the right direction.

If you want more headroom later, we can add: (a) mutual-KNN reordering in the candidate lists to push likely improving edges earlier, (b) a single double-bridge kick when k-opt stalls, and (c) epoch-tagged potentials to eliminate even the O(nK) recompute in some cases.
